<br>
1.  The main reason you can't hold aggro when you want to is because of your level, not your weapons.  If there are a bunch of 60s around you and you're 55 it's just going to be natural.  Also, if the mobs are over 50 it's twice as hard to taunt off someone higher level.  My warrior leveled slower than the rest of my normal group because I was leveling 2 characters at the same time.  I had a hard time keeping aggro when the SK and Paladin were 60 and I was like 57 or 58.  Once I got 60 and epics it became much much easier though.  Actually, I got epics at 59 and while they taunt nicely I did have much more success when I actually got 60.<br>
<br>
2.  Tell the enchanter and shaman not to debuff right at the start if you can afford it.  The longer they wait, the more time you have to build up aggro; even if it's 10-15 seconds.<br>
<br>
3.  You mentioned this but continue to use distance aggro management.  Kael would be the easiest place to use this since the giants have such a large melee range.  <br>
<br>
4.  If you have 2 or more groups at most of these places, having a main tank isn't all that important.  Even the general stuff in SG that hits for 300ish isn't too bad with more than one group.  I've never done rats in DN with more than like 9 people and they drop fast as it is.  Giants aren't all that difficult to slow and once they are they're pretty weak.  Now if you're talking about mobs that hit for 500+ like Dlammaz or something then you'd need to hold aggro but otherwise it's not that necessary with multiple groups. <p>~Tunare's Enforcer~<br>
